{"author":{"id":"044c4525cc6cf713671bb679c18cbfe418f11b1bf91a421387d0e7269263ed51"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1780758572,"nonce":"OIa3/3uCLg84yiwWk8uPihzjtEc=","metadata":{"github-id":"IC_kwDOQ8wE5M8AAAABFIcPtg","github-url":"https://github.com/Enapter/mcp-server/issues/17#issuecomment-4639362998"},"message":"For MCP clients, I would make the authorization surface explainable enough that the agent can decide whether to retry, ask the user, or avoid the action. A plain forbidden result is hard to use safely.\n\nA small machine-readable policy hint would help:\n\n- resource/action being checked\n- required permission or role, without exposing secrets\n- current principal/account scope\n- whether the denial is permanent, needs user consent, or needs a different credential\n- a policy/version identifier that can be logged with the attempted tool call\n\nThat last field is useful for AgentFolio/SATP-style evidence trails: the trust record should not only say “agent was denied,” it should say which policy boundary denied which attempted action. It keeps authorization local to Enapter while giving downstream audit/reputation systems a durable receipt.","files":null}]}